          "body": "The psalm's closing movement is its most carefully constructed. Two botanical images define the righteous: the palm tree (tamar) and the cedar of Lebanon (erez). Both are chosen precisely. The palm is upright, productive in every season, its fruit sweet and sustaining — in Canaan a symbol of flourishing life. The cedar is massive, long-lived, aromatic, storm-resistant — and the very material of the Jerusalem temple. To grow like a cedar is to be associated with the place where God dwells. The location confirms the portrait: 'planted in the house of the LORD, they will flourish in the courts of our God' (92:13). Planting is passive — God is the planter. Flourishing is active and ongoing — the righteous are not merely surviving in God's presence but producing. Verse 14 is the psalm's most astonishing claim: 'they will still yield fruit in old age; they shall be full of sap and very green.' Old age in the ancient world was the season of decline and diminishing. The psalm inverts this entirely. Proximity to the LORD does not plateau — it sustains and deepens productivity through every season of life. And the purpose of this fruitfulness is explicitly stated in verse 15: 'to declare that the LORD is upright; He is my rock, and there is no unrighteousness in Him.' The righteous man's life is not just his own blessing — it is a public argument for God's character. His fruitfulness in God's courts declares to every observer that the God who planted him there is straight, reliable, and entirely free of unrighteousness."
