        "title": "The fool's misreading — prosperity of the wicked and the eternal pivot",
        "range": "92:6-9",
        "excerpt": "A senseless man has no knowledge, nor does a stupid man understand this: that when the wicked sprouted up like grass and all who did iniquity flourished, it was only that they might be destroyed forevermore. But You, O LORD, are on high forever.",
        "body": "This is the theological center of Psalm 92, and it is one of the Old Testament's most direct answers to the theodicy question that haunts Psalms 37, 49, 73, and the book of Job. The 'senseless man' (baar — brutish, animal-like) and the 'stupid man' (kesil — the Proverbs fool) share a single deficiency: they cannot read God's providence. Their failure is not intellectual but moral — they lack the fear of the LORD that is the beginning of wisdom (Proverbs 9:10), and therefore they cannot interpret the apparent prosperity of the wicked correctly.\n\nThe psalmist supplies the correct interpretation in verse 7. The wicked do not flourish despite God — they flourish within His sovereign purpose, and that purpose is their own destruction. The phrase 'only that they might be destroyed forevermore' is not vindictive gloating; it is a statement about divine patience and its terminus. Paul makes the same argument in Romans 9:22: God endures with much patience vessels of wrath prepared for destruction. The wicked's prosperity is the full measure God allows before the judgment that their flourishing makes irreversible. Calvin notes in his commentary on this psalm that the apparent disorder in providence is not evidence of God's inattention but of His patience — He allows sin to ripen before He acts.\n\nVerse 8 is the psalm's structural pivot and its greatest single verse: 'But You, O LORD, are on high forever.' The contrast with verse 7 is total. The wicked's 'forever' (ad, v.7) is destruction — their eternity is annihilation. God's forever is marom — the exalted height, the heavenly enthronement that no enemy can reach or overturn. This single clause is the hinge on which the entire psalm turns. Everything before it (the fool's misreading, the wicked's grass-like flourishing) is the problem. Everything after it (the certainty of enemies' perishing, the righteous's flourishing like cedars) is the solution. The solution is not a new argument — it is a Person. 'But You, O LORD, are on high forever.'\n\nVerse 9 then draws the inference: 'For, behold, Your enemies, O LORD — for, behold, Your enemies will perish.' The double hinneh (behold) is the Hebrew attention-device for something demanding to be seen. The enemies' destruction is announced twice because the psalmist wants the congregation to really look at it. Note that they are 'Your enemies' before they are the psalmist's foes — the conflict is first between the LORD and those who oppose Him, and only derivatively between the psalmist and his adversaries. This reframing is pastorally significant: the believer who is opposed by the wicked is not primarily in a personal conflict — he is caught in a cosmic one whose outcome is already settled.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Baar* (senseless, v.6) — from the root for cattle, beast; the one who thinks like an animal, without moral or theological intelligence. *Kesil* (stupid, v.6) — appears over 50 times in Proverbs; the self-confident fool who resists instruction. *Marom* (on high, v.8) — the exalted height of God's throne. *Hinneh* (behold, v.9, ×2) — the Hebrew interjection demanding the listener look directly at what follows."
