        "excerpt": "But You have exalted my horn like that of the wild ox; I have been anointed with fresh oil.",
        "body": "The pivot in verse 8 from problem to solution resolves not only at the cosmic level (God's enemies perish, v.9) but at the personal level. Verses 10-11 are the psalmist's testimony of experienced vindication. 'You have exalted my horn like that of the wild ox.' The reem (wild ox) was the largest, most formidable land animal known to the ancient Near East — untamable, massive, powerful. The horn of the wild ox was the image of irresistible strength. To have God exalt your horn 'like that of the reem' is to receive a restoration of strength and dignity so complete that it exceeds what any human adversary could diminish.\n\nThe fresh oil of verse 10 carries the resonance of anointing — priestly consecration (Exodus 29:7), royal installation (1 Samuel 16:13), and general divine favor (Psalm 23:5). The psalmist has not anointed himself; God has acted on him. This is the passive voice of divine grace: 'I have been anointed.' The one who had been pressed down by enemies (implied in the 'foes' of v.11) now stands exalted and consecrated by God's direct action.\n\nVerse 11 closes the personal vindication with the sensory testimony of witness: 'My eye has looked exultantly upon my foes, my ears hear of the evildoers who rise up against me.' The psalmist has seen with his own eyes the downfall he was promised. He has heard with his own ears the news of those who rose against him meeting their end. This is not revenge fantasy — the language is retrospective and factual. What God announced would happen to His enemies (v.9) has happened, visibly and audibly, to the psalmist's specific adversaries.\n\nThe structure of these two verses — cosmic principle (vv. 8-9) immediately followed by personal testimony (vv. 10-11) — is pastorally intentional. The Sabbath worshiper is not invited to believe an abstraction; he is invited to share the psalmist's experienced vindication. The one who enthroned forever (v.8) is also the one who anoints with fresh oil (v.10). The gap between cosmic sovereignty and personal care is bridged by the psalmist's own life.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qeren* (horn, v.10) — animal horn as the standard metonym for strength and dignity (see also Psalm 75:4-5; 89:17; 1 Samuel 2:1). *Reem* (wild ox) — translated 'unicorn' in KJV; certainly a powerful, real bovine (possibly aurochs). *Raan* (fresh, green, v.10) — the same root appears in v.14 describing the righteous as 'very green' in old age, connecting the psalmist's anointing to the righteous's later vitality."
